claim_hist.clmhistevaluw:
2017: Loss runs from AWAC show two open claims with total of $13646 paid. Both occurred in the 2016 policy period.
KY: Liquidator of the KY health Cooperative filed suit against the applicant and CEO of KY Health Cooperative/Board of directors and CGI Technologys and Solutions alleging Breach of contract negligence breach of fiduciary duty. The KY Health Cooperative was started in 2011 to provide health insurance coverage to KY residents and went into rehabilitation in 2015.
Applicant assisted in formation including assisting with applying for loans under ACA licensing and assisting in identifying and screening some of the directors and helped with finding CGI Technologys as the TPA. Applicant's contract expired in 2013 and they did not participate in setting premiums or have a role in designing the benefits. It enrolled more members than anticipated but most participants had greater medical needs than anticipated. KY relied on the anticipated funding from ACA to make up the shortfall but the government failed to pay and KY was placed into liquidation. Have filed for arbitration in federal court--waiting for reply.
Applicant has ceased working with health exchanges and health cooperatives.

claim_hist.clmhistevaluw:
Had an issue in 2006 with the AZ Dept of Ag involving a pesticide application to green onions. Problem in the computer program he was using that rounded up amount to apply based on rates for lettuce instead of rates for onions. He was fined $150 for what the Dept of Ag described as a "non-serious violation." He corrected by updating computer and changed to a more updated program for application calculations / recommendations from EPA.
Had another issue in 2002 where farmer told him field was all leaf lettuce but endive was intermixed. Complaint filed against him by County Ag Commission. Was able to fight the complaint because there was documentation that the farmer had filed a permit that he was planting leaf lettuce not endive. Since then Jeffrey does not make any EPA based recommendations to growers without a detailed planting schedule that could show potential for intermixed crops.
We had notice of circumstance in 2009 that never turned into a claim against our insured. He recommended a certain pesticide be used on watermelons and the watermelons had some burning on upper 2 layers of leaves. The claim was settled between the owner of the crop and Valent Chemical Company in that Valents label for the pesticide had error(s). Valent Chemical has pulled the melon label pending further testing on melons which means Insured should not be recommending this option.
2012 - no claims. 2013 - no new claims 2014 - no new claims 2015: This will be our 9th yr - no new claims 2016: This will be our 10th year - no new claims 2017: 11th year - no new claims.

claim_hist.clmhistevaluw:
2009: Has given notice of potential incident to current carrier. No claim has been made yet. The situation involves a situation where the client has not paid. When following up for payment indicated that they may be a problem. This has just happened and too soon to determine if claim is more than dispute over fees. Carrier is considering a notice only and has pointed to an exclusion in the policy that may apply. Reservation letter is dated 2/19/09.
2/4/10 loss runs show is still open with nothing paid. "yes" answers on app refer to this situation.
2011: Hiscox loss runs show that claim is closed with $207005 paid. Of that $125000 was settlement and $82005 was claims expense. Per the insured this claims expense included attorneys fees as well as consulting with experts. This was in excess of a $5000 deductible.
The claim involved problems with tile recommended by the insured for use in the Mondrian Hotel in Miami Beach. There were three types of tile being installed in various areas of the hotel. Some tile was damaged when received; other tile warped after installation. The insured had worked with the contractor and property owner to replace damaged/warped tile. When the Insured followed up for payment due on the project the contractor brought up additional problems with the tile. The Insured placed a lien on the property on 2/24/09 once they were told that payment was not coming.
In notes provided by the Insured it appears that they initially made good faith effort to resolve the issues with the tile. The principal visited the jobsite as well as finding replacement materials in quick fashion. (1 day after being told tile warped.) After a resolution could not be reached applicant then placed a lien on the hotel.
Note: The Hiscox loss run shows claimant as GT Construction while the settlement agreement shows 1100 West Properties LLC. GT was the contractor and 1100 West Properties as subsidiary of Morgans Hotel Group is the owner of the property.
Since this claim they have implemented additional client approval documentation process. **************************************** 2012: No new claims--continues to be claim free with Capitol. ************* 2013: Continues to be claim free ****** 2014: Claim free with Capitol ****** 2015: No new claims ****** 2016: No new claims ****** 2017: One open claim of 6/5/2017: problems with tile provided for hotel renovation job Claim Number: 00185330. $15000 reserve set. ****** 2018: Above claim still open. Will monitor this claim to see final result. Will also request steps taken to prevent future claims.

claim_hist.clmhistevaluw:
Details of the Loss:
A client of Kemper/Unitrin's home burned down and the client suffered a total loss. Kemper/Unitrin paid the client the full coverage amount the homeowner's policy would allow. The cost of replacing the client's home exceeded the coverage amount and the client was suing Kemper/Unitrin for the total cost to rebuild the home and replace the contents. Kemper/Unitrin attached Millennium Information Services and Reliable Reports to the suit.
Kemper/Unitrin contended that they ordered a High Value Report on the home in 2002 from Millennium. At the time the ordering was done via email. Kemper/Unitrin could not provide any documentation that indicated that a high value report was ordered. The loss occurred in Texas where Millennium subcontracted to 2 other vendors: Reliable Reports for standard value inspections or Castle Inspections for high-value inspections. The order was sent to Reliable which indicates that a standard value report was ordered.
In addition Kemper received a standard inspection report and used that to set the coverage amounts on the home. There is a distinct difference between a high-value and a standard value report and during questioning Kemper's representative agreed that any underwriter would know the difference. At the time Kemper was reviewing the report if they had wanted a high-value report they could have easily re-ordered one but they did not. Kemper contended that they would have had the coverage correct had Millennium/Reliable performed a high-value inspection.
On advice of counsel and with approval from our E&O carrier Millennium and Reliable offered a settlement to Kemper to be released from the suit and any other claims that may arise from this suit in the future. The settlement amount was substantially less than it would have cost to defend this at trial.
If Millennium had been able to produce a record that Kemper had in fact ordered a standard value inspection then we would not have been attached to the suit by Kemper. In 2002 Property inspections were ordered via email and entered into our order system manually. Today all inspection orders are placed electronically either through a system-to-system order interface or through the client's direct entry of order information into Millennium's order management system. In either situation the client is required to provide the type of inspection being requested and the client account number on Millennium's system (each of which is specific to inspection type). These order records maintain the identity and method of order entry and date and time stamped and are archived and accessible in our system in perpetuity.

claim_hist.clmhistevaluw:
Applicant experienced a security incident. This is what the agent provided: On 11/27/17 IBN was victimized by a cyber-attack involving a new iteration of a ransomware virus. This is the first such event in the 18 year history of the company. The timing of the attack proved to be VERY bad luck for IBN as the attack occurred during a routine data backup thus allowing the ransomware to infect not only the primary servers but the backup data as well. For this reason IBN chose to pay the $87000 ransom the following day in Bitcoin. $50000 of this loss was covered by Hartford.
Immediately following the attack IBN engaged the services of Monster Cloud a consulting firm specializing in malware and virus cyber-attacks. With Monster's help all servers were scrubbed of the virus and service was restored.
The following remedial measures have been employed to prevent future attacks:
* Newly hired IT/Cyber Security Manager whose job will include monitoring system security and updating protections as necessary. * Removed SAP groups to different environment. * All data will now go through multiple firewalls - NetScaler Hitman Pro and Bit Defender. * All users and customers were required to change passwords. Additional password changes will be required of all users monthly.
